Context:
The existing test files mock various dependencies. For telemetry testing, mock `./telemetry.js` to capture trackEvent calls:
```
const mockTrackEvent = vi.fn();
const mockGetSessionId = vi.fn().mockReturnValue('test-session-id');
vi.mock('./telemetry.js', () => ({
  trackEvent: mockTrackEvent,
  getSessionId: mockGetSessionId,
}));
```

Then in each test, verify:
```
expect(mockTrackEvent).toHaveBeenCalledWith('plugin_installed', {
  session_id: 'test-session-id',
  source: 'side_panel',
});
```

For privacy verification, add a helper that checks no call to mockTrackEvent includes forbidden keys:
```
const assertNoPrivacyViolation = (calls: unknown[][]) => {
  for (const [, props] of calls) {
    const p = props as Record<string, unknown>;
    expect(p).not.toHaveProperty('plugin_name');
    expect(p).not.toHaveProperty('plugin');
    expect(p).not.toHaveProperty('query');
    expect(p).not.toHaveProperty('error_message');
    expect(p).not.toHaveProperty('version');
  }
};
```

Read the existing test patterns in each file to match the mocking style (some use vi.mock at module level, others use vi.spyOn). Follow the existing pattern in each file.

Constraints:
- Match the existing test style in each file — do not introduce a new testing pattern
- The tests should verify ABSENCE of private data, not just presence of expected data
- For extension-handlers.test.ts, the tests will need the existing state/callback mocking infrastructure already present in that file
